    "body": "### Problem\n\nI believe inline extmarks are not positioned properly for unicode text in neovim 0.10. The position that I give for the inline text to appear doesn't seem to be correctly taken into account for multibyte text\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\ncreate an empty file, enter the text:\r\n0123456789\r\n\r\nthen run this lua command:\r\n```\r\n:lua vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark(0, vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(''), 0, 5, {virt_text={{\"<--5\", \"TestHl\"}}, virt_text_pos=\"inline\"})\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou see 01234<-556789\r\n\r\nThis is correct.\r\n\r\nNow open a new file, containing:\r\nšššššššššššš\r\n\r\nrun the same lua command. The inline text does not appear at all.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nthe behavior should be consistent whether it's multibyte text or not.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.0 Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1713484068\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno application\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nlinux fedora 40\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty, same in neovide\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\ngithub release binary",
